1. e4 {Welcome to the
chapter on the Old Steinitz Defense. Given the name, this move has become less
fashionable recently, but still needs to be treated with care. Black is solid,
and hopes for quick development and a fair middlegame. We need to strike
instantly with d4! The theory is a little more "forcing" here. There are only
a number of ways the game can truly progress, and we will cover them all in
this chapter.   One thing to be aware of is the different move orders. I
explain this in the video relating to this chapter in greater depth, but just
be aware if Black plays Bd7 or exd4 first, and also if Black plays Nf6 or exd4
first. Again -- check out the video for the clear explanation between these
move orders, which are likely to transpose.} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d6 4. d4 Bd7 ( 4... exd4 {This move carries little independent value and transposes to 4...
Bd7 lines.} 5. Nxd4 Bd7 6. Nc3 ) 5. Nc3 exd4 ( 5... Nf6 {Has little independent
value, and will likely transpose after Bxc6!} 6. Bxc6 Bxc6 ( 6... bxc6 7. dxe5 dxe5 8. Nxe5 ) 7. Qe2 exd4 8. Nxd4 Be7 9. Be3 ) 6. Nxd4 Nf6 ( 6... Nxd4 7. Bxd7+ Qxd7 8. Qxd4 Nf6 9. Bf4 Be7 10. O-O-O O-O 11. e5 Ne8 12. Nd5 Rd8 13. Rhe1 a6 14. Nxe7+ Qxe7 15. exd6 Qh4 16. Bg3 ( 16. d7 {Would have been stronger!} Nf6 17. Bxc7 Qxd4 18. Rxd4 Rxd7 19. Rxd7 Nxd7 20. Re7 ) 16... Qxd4 17. Rxd4 Nxd6 18. Red1 f6 19. Bxd6 cxd6 20. Rxd6 Rde8 21. c3 Re2 22. R1d2 Re1+ 23. Kc2 Re7 24. Rd7 Kf7 25. c4 Rc8 26. Kc3 Rc5 27. R2d5 Rc8 28. b4 Re8 29. Rxe7+ Rxe7 30. a4 Rc7 31. Kd4 Ke6 32. f4 h6 33. f5+ Ke7 34. c5 Kf7 35. b5 axb5 36. axb5 Ke7 37. Rd6 Kf7 38. b6 Re7 39. c6 bxc6 40. Rxc6 Rd7+ 41. Kc5 g6 42. Rc7 Ke7 43. Rxd7+ Kxd7 44. fxg6 {1-0 (44) Stimpson,P (1946)-Calvert,J (1552) Bournemouth 2016} ) 7. Bxc6 Bxc6 ( 7... bxc6 8. Qf3 Be7 ( 8... c5 {Is a common try for Black. We
park the Knight on f5, where it sits very nicely, and we want to 0-0-0 and
play for a quick attack on the Kingside.} 9. Nf5 h6 ( 9... Bxf5 10. exf5 Be7 11. g4 $1 ) 10. Bf4 Rb8 11. O-O-O g6 12. Ne3 Nh5 13. e5 Nxf4 14. Qxf4 Rb4 15. Qf3 Bg7 16. exd6 cxd6 17. Rxd6 O-O 18. Ned5 Qg5+ 19. Kb1 Be6 20. Re1 Bxd5 21. Rxd5 Qh4 22. Re4 Qxh2 23. a3 Rb6 24. Rxc5 Rf6 25. Qe3 Qxg2 26. f4 h5 27. Nd5 Rd6 28. f5 Kh7 29. f6 Bxf6 30. Nxf6+ Rxf6 31. Ka2 Qf2 32. Qc3 Rf3 33. Qb4 Kg7 34. a4 Rf5 35. Qc3+ Kh7 36. Rc7 h4 37. Qb4 Kg7 38. Rxh4 a5 39. Qc3+ Rf6 40. Qh3 Rf3 41. Rh7+ Kf6 42. Rc6+ Ke5 43. Qd7 Qd4 44. Qe7+ Kf4 45. Rh4+ {1-0 (45) Sutovsky,
E (2700)-Guliev,S (2500) Baku 2011} ) 9. e5 dxe5 10. Nxc6 ) 8. Qe2 Be7 9. Be3 O-O ( 9... Nxe4 10. Nxc6 Nxc3 11. Nxd8 Nxe2 12. Nxb7 Rb8 13. Na5 ) ( 9... Bxe4 10. Nxe4 Nxe4 11. Nf5 O-O ( 11... g6 12. Bd4 ) 12. Qg4 ) 10. f3 Nd7 11. O-O-O Re8 12. g4 Nb6 13. Qd3 Bf8 14. Nf5 Bd7 15. h4 Be6 16. h5 Nc4 17. Bf4 b5 18. g5 c6 19. Nd4 Ne5 20. Qf1 b4 21. Nxe6 Rxe6 22. Ne2 Qa5 23. Kb1 c5 24. Nc1 Qc7 25. Qh3 Rae8 26. Rd5 c4 27. Ne2 c3 28. b3 a5 29. Nd4 a4 30. bxa4 Nc4 31. g6 Na3+ 32. Ka1 Qc4 33. Qf1 $2 ( 33. h6 {!! Was the winning move. The h-file will open up!} ) 33... Qc8 34. gxf7+ Kxf7 35. Bc1 Rf6 36. Bxa3 bxa3 37. Qb5 Kg8 38. Rb1 Rf7 39. a5 Ra7 40. Rf5 Be7 41. Nc6 Ra8 42. Qd5+ Kh8 43. h6 Bf8 44. Rxf8+ Rxf8 45. hxg7+ Kxg7 {1-0 (45) Grigoriants,S (2506)-Kilicaslan,H (2260) Istanbul 2003} *